{{italic title}}
{{primary sources|date=October 2014}}
[[File:Harris' Encyclopedia.JPG|thumb|''Harris' Minor Encyclopedia'', 1803]]
'''''Harris' Minor Encyclopedia''''' is small [[encyclopedia]] compiled by The Rev. [[Thaddeus Mason Harris]] in 1803 in [[Dorchester, MA|Dorchester]], [[Massachusetts]], and published that year in [[Boston]] by [[West and Greenleaf]].<ref>Title page, Minor Encyclopedia, Boston, 1803</ref> It was a revised American edition of ''[[Kendal's Pocket Encyclopedia]]'', edited extensively by Harris. It consists of four volumes of approximately 300 pages each in [[Book size|duodecimo]] (4 1/2 inches by 7 inches). There are no plates. 

Harris covers the [[arts]] and [[sciences]], and [[technology]], and topics of [[general knowledge]], but there are no [[geographical]], [[biographical]], or [[historical]] articles. The editor states, "Articles of local geography have been purposely omitted. The publications of Dr. Morse supersede the necessity of their introduction here...Biographical dictionaries, particularly those of Watkins and Jones, are in general circulation; and the public are expecting an elaborate and complete "Universal Biography," compiled by a Society of Literati in Albany. Nor was it possible to make these volumes the vehicle of HISTORICAL INFORMATION. It is a subject too extensive for our plan."<ref>The preface, ''Minor Encyclopedia'', Boston, 1803</ref>

